         <div type="translation">
            <p>. . . ] great dangers, having fought bravely in all the wars which beset his country, having guarded the forts entrusted to him by the city and preserved faith to the common interest (?) in the most difficult circumstances, having filled all the magistracies with integrity and justice and to the advantage of the city, having been stephanephoros and gymnasiarch, in which offices he was magnificently generous, having held the priesthood of Rome, having been agoranomos at a time of most serious famine and provided corn at a fair price at his own expense, [having held] offices in the wars [.. .</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>See <title>Aphrodisias and Rome</title>, 150-156.</p>
